entry.title: Reland "Reduce string conversion cost in style property setters."
entry.content:
This is a reland of commit 04d9f1126b69ccb4ce93c4b3cc3dd04010687e43



v8::String::WriteOneByte() seemingly adds a zero terminator, causing

a one-byte stack overflow. Add the v8::String::NO_NULL_TERMINATION

option to fix the issue.



Original change's description:

> Reduce string conversion cost in style property setters.

>

> When setting x.style.y = z (and we don't hit the special path where z

> is a double), we need to convert z from a v8::String to something that

> we can work with in our C++ parsers. (Unfortunately, it seems we mostly

> cannot just peek into its contents, possibly because it could be moved

> around by garbage collection.) In our existing code, we convert

> implicitly to WTF::String, which causes heap allocation and some hashing.

>

> However, recently CSSTokenizer was changed to support tokenizing

> from StringView instead. In the vast majority of cases, this means

> we don't need to actually heap-allocate anything; we can write out

> the string into a stack buffer and send in a StringView.

>

> linux-perf Pinpoint (95% CI, no PGO):

>

> motionmark_ramp_canvas_arcs [ -1.7%, +0.8%]

> motionmark_ramp_canvas_lines [ -6.0%, +2.2%]

> motionmark_ramp_design [ +0.8%, +5.1%]

> motionmark_ramp_images [ -0.1%, +3.3%]

> motionmark_ramp_leaves [ -0.7%, +1.5%]

> motionmark_ramp_multiply [ +1.7%, +3.2%]

> motionmark_ramp_paths [ +2.2%, +9.2%]

> motionmark_ramp_suits [ +0.4%, +1.6%]

>

> M1 appears to be unchanged, win-10-perf has only small improvements.

>

entry.title: Remove two Screen AI service TODOs from browser interface binders.
entry.content:
Two infeasible TODOs related to Screen AI service are removed from

browser interface binders. The TODOs suggest ensuring that the

interfaces to the service are added only if user settings indicate

that the service is needed. However, since the service runs totally

local and does not have any privacy concerns, both interfaces may be

used without any user settings:

- Main Content Extraction is available to any user who opens the

sidebar without any settings.

- OCR can be triggered from inaccessible PDFs for any user who has

enabled screen reader, however screen reader is not a strong signal

for the service need and we will be using it with other assistive

technologies soon. The service is also used by local image search

feature on ChromeOS Ash.

entry.content:
Define `GraphInfo` mojo struct to describe an entire WebNN graph

information, it holds the list of all operands descriptor, the indices

of the input/output operands into/out this graph and the operators in

the order of execution.

The `Operator` mojo struct represents the operations defined in

`MLGraphBuilder`, it has the type of operator and the indices of the

input/output operands into/out this operator.

The `OperandDesc` mojo struct represents the `MLOperandDescriptor` to

hold the type, dimensions and addition information.

revert both and wait for the revert to reach both Lacros and Ash.

entry.title: WindowsSystemProxyResolverImplTest: Call SetLastError() when running failure tests.
entry.content:
These tests validate the http error codes, which are mocked, as well as

the Windows error codes, which are not mocked. As such, arbitrary

code that runs during initialization of the test suite/class can result

in unexpected windows error codes. This change updates the test to

explicitly set the error code to the expected value, thus "mocking" the

result.

entry.title: wm: WindowMirrorView created by DragWindowController should sync_bounds
entry.content:
DragWindowController historically sets sync_bounds=true when mirroring

layers. Post crrev.com/c/2238652 refactoring this flag is missed. Lacros

asynchronously updates the bounds of the source ui::Layer bounds, and it

doesn't propagate to the mirrored layers. So dragging a resizing lacros

window (e.g. dragging from maximized state would "restore" the bounds)

would cause the lacros window to appear "offsetted" and/or "clipped".



This CL fixes that.
